%S A396892 1,1,1,3,23,688,68040,15834409,6855451673
%N A396892 Number of unlabeled maximal 5-degenerate graphs on n vertices.
%C A396892 A graph is d-degenerate if every induced subgraph has minimum degree at most d. It is maximal d-degenerate if by adding any edge the property of being d-degenerate is lost.
%C A396892 Maximal d-degenerate graphs can be obtained from d-dimensional 0-extensions starting with the complete graph on d vertices. A d-dimensional 0-extension of a graph adds a new vertex and connects it to d existing vertices.
%C A396892 Maximal d-degenerate graphs are exactly those minimally d-rigid graphs obtained purely from d-dimensional 0-extensions. A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge. If the original graph is minimally d-rigid, so is the graph obtained from the 0-extension.
%H A396892 Allan Bickle, <a href="https://doi.org/10.20429/tag.2024.000105">A Survey of Maximal k-degenerate Graphs and k-Trees</a>, Theory and Applications of Graphs 0(1), Article 5, 2024.
